## Origin section — the "missing world map" mystery

The section's HTML is actually intact — the SVG map with city labels (Dubai, London, New York, Sydney, Germany, Singapore, Guntur) **is** in the DOM. The reason it appears blank at 1127px is the parent uses `grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2`. Tailwind's `lg` = `1024px`, so at desktop it should show two columns. But the inner `<svg viewBox="0 0 800 420">` lives inside `<div class="w-full max-w-lg">` (max-w-lg = 32rem = 512px), so the SVG is shrunk to a small panel, and the right half of the section is just dark space.

Additionally, the cities are wrapped in `<g opacity="0">` — they're set to opacity 0 and presumably animated in by Framer Motion via scroll/intersection. If Lenis or IntersectionObserver setup is off, they stay invisible.

Fixes:

```html
<!-- give the map room to breathe -->
<div class="relative flex flex-col items-center justify-center bg-black-rich px-6 py-16 lg:py-24">
  <div class="w-full max-w-2xl">   <!-- was max-w-lg -->
    <svg viewBox="0 0 800 420" class="w-full h-auto" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet">
      ...
    </svg>
  </div>
</div>
```

For the city pins, give them an animated default state that doesn't require JS to be visible — progressive enhancement:

```css
/* fallback: cities visible even if JS animation never fires */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  svg g[data-city] { opacity: 1 !important; }
}
```

And in your Framer Motion / GSAP component, set the initial state with a `viewport={{ once: true, margin: "-10%" }}` and a fallback timeout that forces `opacity: 1` after 2s in case the observer fails:

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const t = setTimeout(() => {
    document.querySelectorAll('svg g[data-city]').forEach(g => g.setAttribute('style','opacity:1'));
  }, 2000);
  return () => clearTimeout(t);
}, []);
```

Also: the section parent is `<section id="origin" class="bg-ivory">` but the right half is `bg-black-rich` — that two-tone split is fine, but the section has **no vertical padding** (`bg-ivory` only, no `py-*`). That's why the next section's eyebrow ("OUR PRODUCTS") looks like it touches the ivory panel above. Add padding to the grid or section:

